Grigory Leps: “I’m ready to leap into action, even though I’m 55, not 30”
One of the most successful entertainers on the Russian stage, Grigory Leps, is celebrating his 55th birthday this coming Sunday.
The singer spoke with an Izvestia staff writer ahead of the celebration.
I remember how your “fiftieth” was marked.
There was a special pavilion at the Luzhniki Sports Complex, Gloria Gaynor sang for the birthday boy, and there was a massive fireworks display over the Moscow River.
At that moment, you probably thought about how you’d like to spend your next five years.
Did your plans come to fruition?
If we’re talking about my career, this was a successful period.
I was working a lot, toured throughout the entire country three times, and put on between 120-130 concerts per year.
I released two decent albums.
Of course, today, I’m no longer the person I was, let’s say, 20 years ago.
You can’t fool your biological clock.
Singing like I sang in my 30s is becoming more difficult.
Still, I’m ready to leap into action and I don’t want to stop.
And, with new people, I feel like I’ll reach another level.
And you’re recording a new album with them, the first in three years.
Yes, it’s currently being worked on.
In fact, we already recorded everything in my studio and now we’ll send it off to Los Angeles for mastering.
It’s called “Why are you so serious?”, after a song by the same name, which was co-written with Timati.
It’s still not entirely ready, so we haven’t put it out anywhere yet.
We’ll do this later, when the music video for it has also been filmed.
But we’ll put the album out in November, for the series of my anniversary concerts at Moscow’s Crocus City Hall.
The first-rate American drummer, Chris Coleman, had a hand in your new record.
You, it seems, wanted to entice him to join your touring band?
In my opinion, Coleman is one of the most accomplished drummers in the world today.
He came to me in the studio and recorded his parts.
I invited him to join my group, and I invited Jeremy Colson (a famous drummer who is involved in various projects – Izvestia).
However, for ongoing work in Russia, they put forward, to put it mildly, excessive conditions.
We were talking about compensation between €35,000 and €45,000 per month.
Then, I thought that I would track down worthy musicians in the post-Soviet region.
And I found an excellent drummer, Max Malyshev.
At the end of the day, it’s better to feed your own people (smiling).
From time to time, I want to find fault with one of them, but there’s no reason.
For example, the guitarist Feodor Dosymov is highly respected internationally.
Western music magazines write about him and he is invited to various guitar festivals.
Steve Vai, having listened to him play, said “a new generation of guitarists with a different technique of playing has arrived”.
Your album is being mastered in Los Angeles, American musicians are collaborating with you, but you personally still can’t travel to the United States?
Are you trying to get this ban lifted?
Right now, to be honest, I’m not doing anything.
There are a number of lawyers who are dealing with this issue.
As a musician, I am really very sorry that I can’t get into America.
I’ve mentioned more than a few times that I learn when I’m there.
The more you associate with real professionals, the better.
We’re no dumber than them, but we don’t have the same experience or schools.
Over the course of 70 years, our popular music performers were by no means faced with the same challenges that American musicians have always been tackling.
They have been working towards achieving the highest quality of sound.
And I try to follow the exact same principles.
Now, for some reason, Great Britain has banned me from entering for ten years.
But I will still submit a visa application at the British Embassy every year, so that once again, they permit me to travel, and most importantly, work there.
The rest of Europe is friendly toward me.
As early as August, you have a concert planned in Monaco, and not a private concert, but an advertised one, right?
Yes, there is a great hall in Monte Carlo, the Sporting; I performed there once already.
Now, they have invited me again, and as far as I know, all of the concert tickets have already sold out.
Will you go to the Laima Vaikule Rendezvous Festival, which starts on July 20 in Jūrmala?
She invited me, and of course, I accepted.
Laima is a remarkable singer and a magnificent woman who knows how to express herself, her beautiful vocals, and even whispers.
After the tours and anniversary concerts, as far as I know, you would like to turn, once again, to the work of Vladimir Vysotsky.
You already have two albums with his songs in your discography.
When will the third be out?
Probably next year.
But it will be done in a completely different way.
I want to record around 80-90 of Vysotsky’s songs in the same manner of style he did himself.
Just a voice and a guitar.
No other arrangement.
Our famous musician, Timur Vedernikov, will accompany me.
I’m also going to try and entice Alexander Yakovlevich Rosenbaum to take part in the album.
I walked through the idea with him, we’ve got a good relationship, but he is a busy person, so we’ll have to see what happens.
You’ve also gradually introduced the songs of Boris Grebenshchikov into your repertoire.
Perhaps you’ll also record an album of his stuff later on?
Boris Borisovich is a wonderful person and a magnificent musician.
I’ve bumped into him on several occasions and have asked: can I sing this or that song of his?
He responded: “Grigory, I write songs to be performed”.
Please, give it a go and sing them.
I suppose it would also be interesting to record an album like this.
I have no such plans at the moment, but down the road, in a year or two, if Boris Borisovich doesn’t mind, I might do a project like this.
That is, if you don’t concentrate entirely on the business of your production center.
I suspect that you haven’t yet realized its potential or signed contracts with all the artists of interest to you?
There’s a whole group of performers that I dream of having under my wing, but they are self-sufficient and accomplished individuals.
You mean Sergey Lazarev?
Seryozha is a brilliant singer; I invited him to join me.
I might disagree with something in his repertoire, but he is a professional and he has his own development strategy.
But Alexander Panayotov, whom I mentored in The Voice, is now with my center.
We signed a contract with him and we’re working.
In our pop music scene, singers like him are rare.
It would be a real shame if he falls short of the heights of which he is capable.
I’m trying to select a repertoire for him and film music videos.
I’m hoping for a good outcome.
I’m also trying to promote the other artists with my center: I buy them songs, pay the lyricists, and sometimes their tracks make it into rotation on the television channels and radio stations.
If they don’t reach great heights, I will still bring our cooperation to its logical conclusion.
At the end of the process, they’ll get a recorded album and several music videos.
After that, they can go their own way if they want, and I won’t insist that they return the money invested in them.
Although, I would be pleased if one of them achieves commercial success and pays me the percentage we agreed to in the contract.
But if this doesn’t happen, I don’t intend to pull the plug on anyone.
Let everyone work, find their way, and prove themselves like I proved myself a long time ago.
If tomorrow you were offered a road tour across Ukraine and they guaranteed entry into the country, would you go?
I still get invited to go there.
Generally, we’re talking about private events.
But in terms of a big tour…
I am a man of my country, a Russian citizen; it was my own choice to fly to Syria on the same airplane that crashed later on.
If tomorrow, they say I need to fly to another place in the interests of the state, I will fly.
And I don’t give a damn what bloggers and other critics think about me.
I sincerely regret that we have this type of situation with Ukraine.
As far as I’m concerned, we are one people and we should be together.
I regret that this is unlikely to happen, at least not in the near future.
But before, I was performing 40-50 concerts a year in Ukraine.
They were welcoming like nowhere else.
They are a very grateful audience.
I also collaborated with several Ukrainian artists: Ani Lorak, Sveta Loboda, Artem Loik…
There is a multitude of gifted people in Ukraine, and it is truly unfortunate that they are now unable to fully share their talent with the wider Russian audience.
Music should unite and entertain people.
I would be delighted to invite some top-notch Ukrainian performer to Russia, Slava Vakarchuk for example, and hold a joint concert with him.
But I think, at this time, it’s highly unlikely…
Andrei Okhlopkov has been transferred from the cosmodrome
It came to Kommersant’s attention that the technical director for the Vostochny Cosmodrome, Andrei Okhlopkov, has taken on a job at the Khrunichev State Space Research and Production Center (SSRPC).
Previously, he was de facto in charge of building the Vostochny Cosmodrome, but because of disagreements with the management of the Center for the Operation of Space Ground Based Infrastructure (COSGBI), he was transferred to an enterprise in the Fili neighborhood of Moscow, where he will be engaged in coordinating operations.
There won’t be a replacement for Mr. Okhlopkov: the position of technical director will most likely be eliminated and the job responsibilities will be distributed across COSGBI’s divisions.
Kommersant was told about the fact that Vostochny’s technical director and COSGBI’s deputy head for technological development, Andrei Okhlopkov, had transferred to a job with SSRPC by several senior executives of companies in the space industry, as well as by a government staff worker.
“He has been working in the new position for several weeks already”, clarified Kommersant’s industry sources.
It wasn’t possible to get a prompt response from COSGBI on Thursday, and Mr. Okhlopkov himself was not available for comment.
However, Kommersant’s information was officially confirmed by SSRPC.
He made the decision to transfer to the position of director for the coordination of operations, the enterprise stated. Andrei Okhlopkov, tasked with providing the minimum number of facilities required for the first launch at Vostochny Cosmodrome, fully accomplished this.
Mr. Okhlopkov started working at COSGBI in 2013, having service in the space forces under his belt, specifically at Baikonur and at Plesetsk (at the “northern” cosmodrome, he held the post of deputy commander with the rank of colonel).
In 2009, Andrei Okhlopkov was a defendant in a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly, at his behest, regional businessmen in Arkhangelsk Oblast and Komi Republic were receiving state orders for kickbacks, but they weren’t delivering on their commitments to clean the separable parts of the launch vehicle.
In 2012, a trial by jury found him not guilty.
The responsibilities for the development of technology assigned to him at COSGBI were distributed across various projects, but the most important of them was the construction of the cosmodrome in the Far East.
In an interview with Kommersant, Oleg Ostapenko, who headed up the Federal Space Agency at that time, said frankly that the situation at Vostochny “was already critical in October 2013”.
The fact of the matter is that a strategic mistake was made during planning: the completion of construction and launch of the Soyuz 2.1 launch vehicle were scheduled for the very same time – the end of 2015.
In order to accomplish the launch by the end of the year, they decided to complete construction six months early and deadlines were moved from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process, it was necessary to get more than a little bit inventive: COSGBI specialists started the parallel installation of support equipment at facilities that were still under construction.
The main proponent of this idea was Andrei Okhlopkov.
In spite of the substantial risks, and the fact that it was postponed anyhow (instead of December 2015, the Soyuz was only launched on April 28, 2016), this idea was justified in and of itself, says a Kommersant source at the cosmodrome: “Otherwise, we still wouldn’t have completed a single launch from Vostochny, but would be engaged in construction”.
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who is overseeing the establishment of the cosmodrome, jokingly called Andrei Okhlopkov his “space Susanin”, but more often than not, he was requesting information about the pace of construction from him specifically.
Mr. Okhlopkov also stands out in one’s mind for his straightforwardness; for example, in an interview with Kommersant, he suggested stripping the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Spetsstroi) of its status as the exclusive contractor for Vostochny and working directly with subcontractors: “Why should we put all our eggs in Spetsstroi’s basket?”
This idea found support within the government.
As of 2017, COSGBI took on the duty of principal contractor in order to complete construction and installation work on the launch site and technical facilities by the launch date scheduled for the fourth quarter.
According to Kommersant, the reason for Mr. Okhlopkov’s transfer to a new place of work was a disagreement with COSGBI management about the means for completing construction of the cosmodrome’s facilities and complexes, as well as the methods of working with subcontractors.
“It was decided that it would be better for everyone”, says one of the senior executives involved in the construction of Vostochny.
The government staffer, in turn, calls the decision odd: “He was one of the best experts; it will be difficult to find an equivalent replacement for him”.
According to Kommersant, this won’t be necessary: the position of technical director of the cosmodrome will be eliminated and its functions will be distributed across COSGBI’s divisions.
